Here’s a **clear, interview‑ready comparison of Redux vs Redux Toolkit (RTK)** with examples and best‑practice guidance ✅

***

## ✅ What is Redux?

**Redux** is a state management library for JavaScript apps that uses a **single global store**, **actions**, and **reducers** to manage state in a predictable way.

Problem:  
👉 **Too much boilerplate** (actions, action types, reducers, immutability handling).

***

## ✅ What is Redux Toolkit (RTK)?

**Redux Toolkit** is the **official, recommended way** to write Redux logic.

👉 It wraps Redux with **best practices**, **simpler APIs**, and **less boilerplate**.

> RTK is **not a replacement** for Redux — it is how Redux should be written today.

***

## 🔑 Core Differences at a Glance

| Feature                 | Redux (Classic)                  | Redux Toolkit (RTK)         |
| ----------------------- | -------------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Boilerplate             | ❌ Very high                      | ✅ Minimal                   |
| Actions                 | Manual                           | Auto‑generated              |
| Reducers                | Switch statements                | Slice reducers              |
| Immutability            | Manual (`spread`)                | Automatic (Immer)           |
| Async logic             | redux‑thunk / saga (extra setup) | `createAsyncThunk` built‑in |
| Store setup             | Complex                          | Simple (`configureStore`)   |
| Best practice today     | ❌ No                             | ✅ Yes                       |
| Official recommendation | ❌ Legacy style                   | ✅ Recommended               |

***

| Old Redux         | Redux Toolkit   |
| ----------------- | --------------- |
| Boilerplate heavy | Minimal code    |
| Manual actions    | Auto‑generated  |
| Switch statements | Slice reducers  |
| Error‑prone       | Safe with Immer |

